A ROS2 + Gazebo simulation of a self-balancing two-wheel robot (Segway-style) using PID control and IMU-based sensor fusion.


Project Overview

This project simulates an inverted pendulum two-wheel robot that balances itself upright using real-time IMU feedback and a PID controller. The robot is controlled by user keyboard input which shifts the balance setpoint to produce forward, backward, and turning motion — exactly like a real Segway.

Objective: Simulate a robot that balances itself like a Segway using ROS2, Gazebo, and Python.


Features


PID control loop for real-time balance correction
IMU-based sensor fusion using a Complementary Filter (gyroscope + accelerometer)
Quaternion-based pitch angle estimation for accurate tilt detection
Differential drive simulation via Gazebo plugin
User-controlled navigation (forward, backward, left, right) via keyboard
Tunable PID parameters at runtime without rebuilding
Custom Gazebo world with optimized physics timestep (1000 Hz) for stable simulation



