Control Theory

PID Controller

The balance controller uses a PID (Proportional-Integral-Derivative) controller:

output = Kp * error + Ki * integral(error) + Kd * d(error)/dt

ParameterValueRoleKp4.0Proportional — main correction forceKi0.01Integral — eliminates steady-state leanKd0.6Derivative — dampens oscillationsOutput limit±2.0 m/sPrevents overcorrection

Sensor Fusion — Complementary Filter

Raw IMU data is noisy. A complementary filter fuses:


Gyroscope — accurate short-term rate, drifts over time
Accelerometer — accurate long-term angle, noisy short-term


angle = alpha * (angle + gyro_rate * dt) + (1 - alpha) * accel_angle
alpha = 0.98

Pitch Estimation — Quaternion Method

Instead of raw accelerometer math, pitch is extracted from the IMU orientation quaternion for higher accuracy:

pythonsinp = 2.0 * (w * y - z * x)
pitch = asin(sinp)

Navigation via Setpoint Shifting

User input shifts the balance target angle slightly, making the robot lean and therefore move — exactly like a real Segway:

target = target_angle + user_speed * 0.1
error  = target - pitch


Robot URDF Description

The robot model consists of:


Base link — tall, top-heavy body (0.1 x 0.1 x 0.3 m), mass 1.0 kg
Left wheel — continuous joint, radius 0.05 m
Right wheel — continuous joint, radius 0.05 m
IMU link — fixed at top of body (0.15 m above center)
Diff drive plugin — wheel separation 0.16 m
IMU plugin — 100 Hz update rate
